00:02:58.780 --> 00:03:01.590
I wanted to ask you Pontus
what was the experience

00:03:01.590 --> 00:03:04.950
like of working with
the Graham Company?

00:03:04.950 --> 00:03:08.680
&gt;&gt; Pontus Lidberg: So
the Graham dancers just

00:03:08.680 --> 00:03:12.670
like ballet dancers have
a very strong foundation

00:03:12.670 --> 00:03:17.370
but it's not ballet it's different.

00:03:17.370 --> 00:03:23.420
They are trained equally
specifically and clearly

00:03:23.420 --> 00:03:27.030
but in a different way and
I'm rather used to working

00:03:27.030 --> 00:03:31.360
with ballet dancers
and these dancers came

00:03:31.360 --> 00:03:36.330
with definitely equal amounts
of physicality and clarity

00:03:36.330 --> 00:03:38.970
in their movement but coming
from a different place

00:03:38.970 --> 00:03:42.430
which has informed me as
a choreographer as well

00:03:42.430 --> 00:03:44.070
and it has definitely
informed the work.

00:03:44.070 --> 00:03:48.030 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: And you studied this
technique at some point yourself.

00:03:48.030 --> 00:03:52.020
&gt;&gt; Pontus Lidberg: Yes, well so
I was a trained ballet dancer

00:03:52.020 --> 00:03:56.310
but as part of my education
was various forms

00:03:56.310 --> 00:04:00.820
of contemporary dance movement and
Graham technique was the first one

00:04:00.820 --> 00:04:07.090 position:56%
that I was exposed to but I think
in general Graham was one of the few

00:04:07.090 --> 00:04:09.230
who really codified a technique.

00:04:09.230 --> 00:04:13.230
Other choreographers have a
lineage or a style of training

00:04:13.230 --> 00:04:15.200
but she actually codified
a technique

00:04:15.200 --> 00:04:19.080
but most contemporary
training is not

00:04:19.080 --> 00:04:23.060
like that, it's much more nebulous.

00:04:23.060 --> 00:04:25.600
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: And you've also
commented on the expressivity

00:04:25.600 --> 00:04:27.610
of this particular troupe,

00:04:27.610 --> 00:04:30.920
their facial expressions
and the whole aesthetic.

00:04:30.920 --> 00:04:34.550
&gt;&gt; Pontus Lidberg: This is also
something I very much appreciate

00:04:34.550 --> 00:04:41.130
because the company, the
dancers have a strong confidence

00:04:41.130 --> 00:04:43.020
in their facial expression.

00:04:43.020 --> 00:04:46.860
There are certain movements
of contemporary dance

00:04:46.860 --> 00:04:51.280
where the face is kind
of forgotten on purpose

00:04:51.280 --> 00:04:55.290
where the movement is supposed
to speak and you're not supposed

00:04:55.290 --> 00:04:59.280
to emote with your face but these
dancers' faces are very alive

00:04:59.280 --> 00:05:05.230
and I find that very
inspiring and true to people.

00:05:05.230 --> 00:05:08.410
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: And that's
something that you studied,

00:05:08.410 --> 00:05:10.480
I mean I know it's a
10-year process, right?

00:05:10.480 --> 00:05:11.780
The Graham technique, I think.

00:05:11.780 --> 00:05:14.090
&gt;&gt; Janet Eilber: That's what Martha
used to say that it takes 10 years

00:05:14.090 --> 00:05:22.250
to make a dancer but I think what
Pontus is describing is just the

00:05:22.250 --> 00:05:24.330
element of the Graham
technique which is

00:05:24.330 --> 00:05:30.210
that she created this vocabulary
sort of born out of body language,

00:05:30.210 --> 00:05:34.170
out of natural gesture,
because she wanted

00:05:34.170 --> 00:05:39.700
to describe what she called the
inner landscape, the human emotions

00:05:39.700 --> 00:05:43.510
and conditions rather than
swans and flowers and kings

00:05:43.510 --> 00:05:47.140
and queens she was going for
what was really going on here

00:05:47.140 --> 00:05:49.940
in the late 1920s and 30s

00:05:49.940 --> 00:05:56.240
and the vocabulary she developed
is a combination of the core,

00:05:56.240 --> 00:06:00.740
emotion riding on the breath and
coming from the core of the body

00:06:00.740 --> 00:06:05.000
and her famous contraction and
release which is the energizing

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:11.540
of the torso and it is a perfect
marriage between that physicality,

00:06:11.540 --> 00:06:15.540
the physical vocabulary, and
the emotion that it's describing

00:06:15.540 --> 00:06:18.140
so for Graham dancers
they are really trained

00:06:18.140 --> 00:06:20.600
to illuminate the physical movement

00:06:20.600 --> 00:06:23.970
with an emotional image
in the classroom.

00:06:23.970 --> 00:06:26.330
It's a marriage between the two.

00:06:26.330 --> 00:06:29.450
You will see in Medea tonight

00:06:29.450 --> 00:06:34.040
and Appalachian Spring the
dancers really have to be actors

00:06:34.040 --> 00:06:36.780
as well as incredible athletes.

00:06:36.780 --> 00:06:39.210
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: And even
just in their carriage,

00:06:39.210 --> 00:06:42.460
I mean anyone who has seen a Graham
performance the way they step

00:06:42.460 --> 00:06:45.210
onto the stage is like actors
in a [inaudible] theater

00:06:45.210 --> 00:06:48.240
or anything else, immediate
presence and charisma.

00:06:48.240 --> 00:06:50.300 position:56%
That's something I took away with me

00:06:50.300 --> 00:06:53.500
from the first time I
saw a Graham performance.

00:06:53.500 --> 00:06:59.340
Thinking about the music watching
your work there's such musicality

00:06:59.340 --> 00:07:03.010
and I know you are a musician
first, what was your instrument

00:07:03.010 --> 00:07:05.930
and what made you choose
the path to dance?

00:07:05.930 --> 00:07:13.320
&gt;&gt; Pontus Lidberg: I was trained as
a pianist as a young boy and it was

00:07:13.320 --> 00:07:15.460
as I remember, and
I was pretty young

00:07:15.460 --> 00:07:21.230
so I might not remember everything,
but at 10 you kind of have

00:07:21.230 --> 00:07:27.230 position:56%
to choose professional training for
both music or dance and I auditioned

00:07:27.230 --> 00:07:33.880
for both professional schools
that were available in Stockholm

00:07:33.880 --> 00:07:38.000
and I was accepted into both so I
had to make a choice then and there

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:41.490
and the one thing I
remember is that the audition

00:07:41.490 --> 00:07:47.750 position:56%
for the music classes were on a
Sunday in the winter and I was alone

00:07:47.750 --> 00:07:51.060
with the teacher in a
room and I was singing

00:07:51.060 --> 00:07:56.430
and I guess they were just
testing me and the audition

00:07:56.430 --> 00:07:59.450
for the ballet school was on a
Thursday night and it was full

00:07:59.450 --> 00:08:01.840
of people in the corridors
and in their classrooms

00:08:01.840 --> 00:08:03.890
and on stage training
and running past

00:08:03.890 --> 00:08:06.080
and it felt like a dynamic place.

00:08:06.080 --> 00:08:10.390
I honestly think that that was
a deciding factor [laughter].

00:08:10.390 --> 00:08:11.730
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: Interesting.

00:08:11.730 --> 00:08:16.020
&gt;&gt; Pontus Lidberg: And to add
to that I know many musicians

00:08:16.020 --> 00:08:21.260
and they have a wonderful rich
life and also solace especially,

00:08:21.260 --> 00:08:24.870
a rather lonesome life sitting
by themselves practicing.

00:08:24.870 --> 00:08:29.570
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: Yes, or in a hotel
room touring constantly, it's true.

00:08:29.570 --> 00:08:34.250 position:56%
Thinking about the music for your
work, Irving Fein's lyrical Notturno

00:08:34.250 --> 00:08:38.510 position:56%
for Harp and Strings it's very
interesting for us to see this work,

00:08:38.510 --> 00:08:42.950
people who know the work as a
chamber piece, to see it come

00:08:42.950 --> 00:08:46.650
into a new dimension through
your dance and this reminded me

00:08:46.650 --> 00:08:50.420
of Janet's phrase seeing the
classics through new eyes

00:08:50.420 --> 00:08:52.950
and I was wanting to,
I was thinking too

00:08:52.950 --> 00:08:57.180
about how you re-envisioned
the classic ballet Raymonda.

00:08:57.180 --> 00:09:00.190
Would you like to talk
a little bit about that?

00:09:00.190 --> 00:09:03.970
&gt;&gt; Pontus Lidberg: So
Raymonda is a work I made

00:09:03.970 --> 00:09:06.350
for the Royal Swedish
Ballet about one

00:09:06.350 --> 00:09:10.930 position:56%
and a half years ago was the
premier and it's a classical ballet,

00:09:10.930 --> 00:09:17.050
one of the classics
by Glazunov but not

00:09:17.050 --> 00:09:20.410
that often performed
actually and it's huge.

00:09:20.410 --> 00:09:27.260
It's very long and very big
work and I reinvented it

00:09:27.260 --> 00:09:32.350
by writing a new libretto because
the libretto has a lot of problems

00:09:32.350 --> 00:09:33.810
for our contemporary times.

00:09:33.810 --> 00:09:38.870
It's very racist and it's also
kind of all over the place.

00:09:38.870 --> 00:09:43.680
It's one of those librettos
where you think,

00:09:43.680 --> 00:09:47.780 position:56%
I mean I don't exactly know but I'm
pretty sure that it was written more

00:09:47.780 --> 00:09:51.460
to be able to showcase we want
this kind of Oriental dance here

00:09:51.460 --> 00:09:52.760
and then we want this there,

00:09:52.760 --> 00:09:57.220
kind of like wrote their
libretto haphazardly

00:09:57.220 --> 00:10:00.270
to suit various inspirations.

00:10:00.270 --> 00:10:05.950
But I completely rewrote it
while keeping certain elements

00:10:05.950 --> 00:10:10.040
and it was kind of coming full
circle for me because I was trained

00:10:10.040 --> 00:10:17.390
in ballet but I very early
chose to go a contemporary path.

00:10:17.390 --> 00:10:20.670
I felt like there was more
to do in contemporary dance

00:10:20.670 --> 00:10:25.020
and definitely more to
explore but that training just

00:10:25.020 --> 00:10:27.860
like Graham training is
something you just can't undo.

00:10:27.860 --> 00:10:31.610
I mean it's in my body
so it was interesting

00:10:31.610 --> 00:10:35.120
to come full circle
and revisit that again.

00:10:35.120 --> 00:10:38.390
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: In the
piece with the music,

00:10:38.390 --> 00:10:41.620
with the Fein piece you
actually reordered it slightly

00:10:41.620 --> 00:10:45.520
and made it cyclical I
think you read about -

00:10:45.520 --> 00:10:49.100
&gt;&gt; Pontus Lidberg: So that I did
with Raymonda too by the way.

00:10:49.100 --> 00:10:54.920
I reordered it to suit the
new libretto but with this

00:10:54.920 --> 00:11:00.910 position:56%
with the Notturno for Harp and
Strings I thought that I didn't want

00:11:00.910 --> 00:11:05.160
to illustrate the work
only but I wanted

00:11:05.160 --> 00:11:13.610
to somehow add a new structure
to it and so I added a repeat.

00:11:13.610 --> 00:11:17.430
I framed the work with a
fast section, the animato,

00:11:17.430 --> 00:11:20.170
and then I reordered the two
slow sections and it kind

00:11:20.170 --> 00:11:24.380
of almost became a
mirror or a cycle both.

00:11:24.380 --> 00:11:27.530
It kind of goes to the middle
and then it almost rewinds

00:11:27.530 --> 00:11:31.240
but takes a different path back and
I found that that was interesting

00:11:31.240 --> 00:11:33.940 position:56%
because it also talks to Irving Fein

00:11:33.940 --> 00:11:38.110
which I can't do but
I can add a comment.

00:11:38.110 --> 00:11:40.930
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: It was so nice to
see in the film about your work

00:11:40.930 --> 00:11:44.480
and about this project which you
can see in our lobby here tonight.

00:11:44.480 --> 00:11:47.720
It's so nice to see the
pictures of the composers

00:11:47.720 --> 00:11:51.130 position:56%
that to the Graham Company has
worked with including now this music

00:11:51.130 --> 00:11:55.630
from Irving Fein but you I guess
you found in your archives some

00:11:55.630 --> 00:11:58.080
of those photos to bring out

00:11:58.080 --> 00:12:01.230
and music has always been
a hugely important part

00:12:01.230 --> 00:12:03.610
of what you do choosing
the music and so on.

00:12:03.610 --> 00:12:06.020
For us it's exciting tonight
to have a live orchestra.

00:12:06.020 --> 00:12:08.320
We try every time to
have a live orchestra

00:12:08.320 --> 00:12:11.290
when we can possibly do it
and it sounds fantastic.

00:12:11.290 --> 00:12:15.380
It's a little challenging and we'll
