00:12:19.500 --> 00:12:23.460 position:56%
Regarding your work as a filmmaker
I wanted to ask you to touch on that

00:12:23.460 --> 00:12:27.660
and ask you about how it affects
your vision for your choreography.

00:12:27.660 --> 00:12:33.080
&gt;&gt; Pontus Linberg: It's a
question I get fairly often.

00:12:33.080 --> 00:12:36.170
The first thing I would
say is that when I create

00:12:36.170 --> 00:12:39.980
for film the option I have
which I don't have on stage is

00:12:39.980 --> 00:12:43.210
to completely direct
the eye of the audience.

00:12:43.210 --> 00:12:45.420
I can zoom in on a
button for example

00:12:45.420 --> 00:12:50.680
and that is what everyone will see
in film but when you put something

00:12:50.680 --> 00:12:52.890
on stage you can't do
that, in fact you leave it

00:12:52.890 --> 00:12:58.450 position:56%
to each individual audience member
to follow their own path so you have

00:12:58.450 --> 00:13:01.070 position:56%
to think differently about structure

00:13:01.070 --> 00:13:04.850
and there are very different
ways of working actually.

00:13:04.850 --> 00:13:07.670
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: I was
wondering I was thinking

00:13:07.670 --> 00:13:13.720
about Martha Graham's experiments
in technique and her inspiration

00:13:13.720 --> 00:13:16.360
from the visual arts
and her statement

00:13:16.360 --> 00:13:17.870
on seeing a Kandinsky painting

00:13:17.870 --> 00:13:20.720
in 1926 before she
had even become known

00:13:20.720 --> 00:13:22.570
as a choreographer in New York.

00:13:22.570 --> 00:13:23.870
She looked at the painting

00:13:23.870 --> 00:13:26.820
and her response later was
I will dance like that.

00:13:26.820 --> 00:13:31.400
It's just an extraordinary
comment and I wanted to see Janet

00:13:31.400 --> 00:13:35.690
if you had thoughts on the
visual arts in later Graham works

00:13:35.690 --> 00:13:39.880
and today too how you
are working with visuals.

00:13:39.880 --> 00:13:42.080
&gt;&gt; Janet Eilber: Well Martha
drew great inspiration

00:13:42.080 --> 00:13:44.800
from such a variety of things.

00:13:44.800 --> 00:13:47.910
She was a voracious
reader, she loved poetry.

00:13:47.910 --> 00:13:52.380
When she saw the Kandinsky in '26

00:13:52.380 --> 00:13:57.520
or I thought it was '23 she
was visiting the first exhibit

00:13:57.520 --> 00:14:01.470
in America at the Chicago
Art Institute

00:14:01.470 --> 00:14:06.840
of the European abstract
painters, modern painters,

00:14:06.840 --> 00:14:13.160
and she said she was relieved to
see the exhibit because she was

00:14:13.160 --> 00:14:16.110
so relieved to see that there were
other people who thought the way

00:14:16.110 --> 00:14:19.860
that she did to see
this abstract work

00:14:19.860 --> 00:14:23.400
and the Kandinsky had
a streak of red in it.

00:14:23.400 --> 00:14:26.960 position:56%
She said she would make a dance like
that and that's our dance Diversion

00:14:26.960 --> 00:14:32.380
of Angels from 1948 which is
unfortunately not in this program

00:14:32.380 --> 00:14:35.300
but when she was choreographing
she would bring

00:14:35.300 --> 00:14:43.630
in huge coffee table art books with
specific paintings or sculptures

00:14:43.630 --> 00:14:47.050
or sometimes natural
things, leaves and trees

00:14:47.050 --> 00:14:50.750
that she was drawing inspiration
from on whatever new work

00:14:50.750 --> 00:14:56.780
that she was creating
and it was just one

00:14:56.780 --> 00:15:00.900
of the many ways she filled herself

00:15:00.900 --> 00:15:04.320
with inspiration before
she started to choreograph.

00:15:04.320 --> 00:15:06.130
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: And she
was also very much involved

00:15:06.130 --> 00:15:09.810
in union psychology
studying that as well, right?

00:15:09.810 --> 00:15:11.530
Joseph Campbell and -

00:15:11.530 --> 00:15:13.980
&gt;&gt; Janet Eilber: Joseph Campbell
was married to one of the members

00:15:13.980 --> 00:15:20.470
of her company, Jean Erdman,
yes, so that was in the '40s.

00:15:20.470 --> 00:15:22.680
Erick Hawkins who Martha married

00:15:22.680 --> 00:15:27.810
for a short time had studied the
classics at Harvard and we think

00:15:27.810 --> 00:15:33.340 position:56%
that is why the Greek period
appeared and Erick was inspiring her

00:15:33.340 --> 00:15:37.840
and after she divorced Erick she
was [inaudible] analysis [laughter]

00:15:37.840 --> 00:15:43.460
so she was kind of drawing
inspiration from all over the place

00:15:43.460 --> 00:15:48.720
but the Dark Meadow suite on
tonight's program is a suite

00:15:48.720 --> 00:15:51.740
of highlights from the much
longer work, Dark Meadow,

00:15:51.740 --> 00:15:53.790
and Dark Meadow is considered

00:15:53.790 --> 00:15:57.780
to be her [inaudible] piece
created while she was in analysis

00:15:57.780 --> 00:16:03.600
about life's greatest
adventure, I'll quote it tonight

00:16:03.600 --> 00:16:07.290
in our introduction,
the adventure of seeking

00:16:07.290 --> 00:16:10.740
so it's a ballet about questioning.

00:16:10.740 --> 00:16:16.590
There's no dramatic narrative,
it's about life's journey.

00:16:16.590 --> 00:16:17.920
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: And
this is something,

00:16:17.920 --> 00:16:24.040
these areas that we're talking
about the psyche and myth of poesis

00:16:24.040 --> 00:16:29.080
and so forth, these are very
much in the line of thinking

00:16:29.080 --> 00:16:31.700
of Isamu Noguchi and as many of you

00:16:31.700 --> 00:16:34.440
in the room know we've had the
pleasure of having an exploration

00:16:34.440 --> 00:16:38.060
of the connection between Graham
and Noguchi in the past week.

00:16:38.060 --> 00:16:42.240
It's been really exciting and fun,
something very different for us,

00:16:42.240 --> 00:16:46.770
but I was thinking back to the
art again how she took Noguchi

00:16:46.770 --> 00:16:49.710
to the I think MoMA to
look at a work there

00:16:49.710 --> 00:16:54.450 position:56%
and said this is what I have in mind
and then he said okay I understand

00:16:54.450 --> 00:16:57.910
and I don't think the book that
we were reading [inaudible]

00:16:57.910 --> 00:17:00.220
or his biography sort of says
he didn't really want to go

00:17:00.220 --> 00:17:02.320
to the museum or he didn't
need to go to the museum

00:17:02.320 --> 00:17:06.910
but it just showed me how much
she was involved with this kind

00:17:06.910 --> 00:17:10.100
of visual impetus and so on.

00:17:10.100 --> 00:17:14.170
In talking about him I really got
a kick out of reading an article

00:17:14.170 --> 00:17:18.700
by you where you talked about
the challenges of working

00:17:18.700 --> 00:17:23.030
with these Noguchi set pieces
as a dancer and I'd love it

00:17:23.030 --> 00:17:24.980
if you would talk to
the audience about that.

00:17:24.980 --> 00:17:28.150
&gt;&gt; Janet Eilber: Well it was
a little bit tongue in cheek

00:17:28.150 --> 00:17:32.020
but the dancers really have to --

00:17:32.020 --> 00:17:34.610
, they have a very intimate
relationship with these sets,

00:17:34.610 --> 00:17:37.510
Noguchi designed sets that
are totally practical.

00:17:37.510 --> 00:17:42.500 position:56%
We scramble all over them, we swing
off them, doors open, chairs a spin.

00:17:42.500 --> 00:17:47.440
Tonight in Medea you'll see she
climbs inside this beautiful brass

00:17:47.440 --> 00:17:52.770 position:56%
bush of thorns but they don't always
act exactly as you'd like them

00:17:52.770 --> 00:17:59.010
to act [laughter] and for
example in Appalachian Spring

00:17:59.010 --> 00:18:04.190
because Noguchi used to the angles
of the house to create perspective

00:18:04.190 --> 00:18:09.110
and to give such a beautiful
provocative design to the audience

00:18:09.110 --> 00:18:13.290
but the rocking chair that the
pioneering woman has to sit on for

00:18:13.290 --> 00:18:16.090
so long is about as
big as a bicycle seat,

00:18:16.090 --> 00:18:17.980
you know it's almost
two dimensional.

00:18:17.980 --> 00:18:20.320
At one point you will see
the four followers sit

00:18:20.320 --> 00:18:23.260
on the little bench that's up
against the wall of the house.

00:18:23.260 --> 00:18:27.420
Well that bench is only about
four inches wide and it's raked,

00:18:27.420 --> 00:18:31.470
it's on an angle so they
really can't even perch on it

00:18:31.470 --> 00:18:33.650
so there's all sorts of stories.

00:18:33.650 --> 00:18:38.980
In Cave of the Heart, the
big aorta that is at the back

00:18:38.980 --> 00:18:45.110
of the center stage has
corners, we call it the elephant

00:18:45.110 --> 00:18:49.090 position:56%
because it looks like an elephant on
the back with his feet sticking up,

00:18:49.090 --> 00:18:52.520
and dancers have to step from
corner to corner and not look down

00:18:52.520 --> 00:18:55.990
and look very self-assured as
they walk around this thing

00:18:55.990 --> 00:18:59.030
and it takes a lot of rehearsal.

00:18:59.030 --> 00:19:04.310
There's a little bit of swearing
that goes on I think [laughter].

00:19:04.310 --> 00:19:06.820
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: And I wanted to,
