these innovative ventures.

00:24:25.820 --> 00:24:28.260
&gt;&gt; Janet Eilber: Well that kind
of also speaks to what's going

00:24:28.260 --> 00:24:29.880
on in the dance world these days,

00:24:29.880 --> 00:24:33.120
you know modern dance is
a really young art form.

00:24:33.120 --> 00:24:38.360
It's just over 100 years old now
and it was born out of revolt,

00:24:38.360 --> 00:24:41.940
each generation rejecting what
had gone before and moving forward

00:24:41.940 --> 00:24:49.390
but as we hit our 100th birthday or
so the field itself is looking back

00:24:49.390 --> 00:24:52.400
and saying wait a minute
there are things in our past

00:24:52.400 --> 00:24:54.230
that we don't want to throw away.

00:24:54.230 --> 00:25:00.110
The art form has new classics
and Graham certainly has many

00:25:00.110 --> 00:25:05.500
of these classics but the modern
dance has really not focused on how

00:25:05.500 --> 00:25:08.030
to keep their classics,
how to celebrate them,

00:25:08.030 --> 00:25:12.830
how to keep them relevant, how
to engage audiences with them.

00:25:12.830 --> 00:25:16.810
The audiences for modern
dance really have been trained

00:25:16.810 --> 00:25:20.460
and the funders to appreciate
the new, it's all about the new

00:25:20.460 --> 00:25:27.440
so we've really been experimenting
with how to bring more points

00:25:27.440 --> 00:25:32.990
of access for today's audiences
to our classic works everything

00:25:32.990 --> 00:25:36.720
from simply spoken
introductions on our programs.

00:25:36.720 --> 00:25:40.320
We started by asking well what's
the modern dance equivalent

00:25:40.320 --> 00:25:45.670 position:56%
to a museum's audio tour or to opera
super titles you know how do you

00:25:45.670 --> 00:25:52.130
bring context to the classics so
that audiences can enter into them

00:25:52.130 --> 00:25:57.260
and appreciate their
[inaudible] and beauty.

00:25:57.260 --> 00:26:02.000
So we've done spoken introductions,
we've done contextual programming,

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:05.960
we do season themes like
inner landscape focusing

00:26:05.960 --> 00:26:08.960
on the psychological ballets.

00:26:08.960 --> 00:26:12.590
We're the first company to
stream a rehearsal live.

00:26:12.590 --> 00:26:16.190
We've done online video
competitions.

00:26:16.190 --> 00:26:19.990
We partner with all sorts of
different educational institutions

00:26:19.990 --> 00:26:26.950
and cultural institutions and our
school has many creative projects

00:26:26.950 --> 00:26:29.940
and this has all led us
to commissioning new work

00:26:29.940 --> 00:26:33.100
because we believe there's a real
conversation between new work

00:26:33.100 --> 00:26:36.150
and the classic works and
we've discovered by having both

00:26:36.150 --> 00:26:40.790
on our programs it's really kind
of a one plus one makes three.

00:26:40.790 --> 00:26:45.290
The classics bring a
context to the new work

00:26:45.290 --> 00:26:49.020
and the new work brings
fresh eyes to the classics

00:26:49.020 --> 00:26:52.740
and so that's a very short --
, it's not such a short answer,

00:26:52.740 --> 00:26:55.800
but I could be much longer
on that topic I'll tell you.

00:26:55.800 --> 00:26:57.330
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: That's the
