from multiple angles with different
cameras and it dawned on me

00:31:49.870 --> 00:31:54.740
that it must have taken multiple
takes and been a real challenge

00:31:54.740 --> 00:31:56.620
for the dancers perhaps so
I was wondering since both

00:31:56.620 --> 00:31:59.840
of you are working in film if
you could talk a little bit

00:31:59.840 --> 00:32:02.780
about that both what it's like
for the dancers to have to go

00:32:02.780 --> 00:32:06.720
through the same piece especially
if the cameras could be moving

00:32:06.720 --> 00:32:12.500
or shooting them from
different angles?

00:32:12.500 --> 00:32:17.550
&gt;&gt; Pontus Lidberg: Well that's
kind of normal for film work.

00:32:17.550 --> 00:32:21.660 position:56%
Either you have a lot of money and
you have and A camera and a B camera

00:32:21.660 --> 00:32:25.600
and a C camera and you have
somehow arranged that they are not

00:32:25.600 --> 00:32:28.520
in each other's path
so they are not filmed,

00:32:28.520 --> 00:32:31.530
that one camera doesn't
film the other camera,

00:32:31.530 --> 00:32:34.090
and you try to have few takes
and that's very expensive

00:32:34.090 --> 00:32:40.090
but you win time or you usually
have smaller budgets and that's 99%

00:32:40.090 --> 00:32:44.140
of the time true and you have
only one crew and one camera

00:32:44.140 --> 00:32:48.730
and instead you have to do one
set up and then you have to move

00:32:48.730 --> 00:32:54.420
to another one and change the lens
and so on but there's enough rest

00:32:54.420 --> 00:32:56.790
in between and it's
not really a problem.

00:32:56.790 --> 00:33:00.560
&gt;&gt; Janet Eilber: I don't
know about that [laughter].

00:33:00.560 --> 00:33:05.100
I've been in a few dance films
where we did it again and again

00:33:05.100 --> 00:33:06.900
and you had to stop and prepare -

00:33:06.900 --> 00:33:08.200
&gt;&gt; Pontus Lidberg:
It's certainly tiring.

00:33:08.200 --> 00:33:10.050
&gt;&gt; Janet Eilber: the needs
of the costume, it's tiring,

00:33:10.050 --> 00:33:15.520 position:56%
and of course dancers -- , Bob Fosse
said dancers are the last soldiers

00:33:15.520 --> 00:33:19.320
of the theater because they
really are disciplined and work

00:33:19.320 --> 00:33:23.940
to get something right so we will
do take after take after take.

00:33:23.940 --> 00:33:26.970
&gt;&gt; Pontus Lidberg: Yes
but I think what's --

00:33:26.970 --> 00:33:31.460
, as long as there's a clear
goal why it's not a problem

00:33:31.460 --> 00:33:35.300
and of course you don't destroy
anyone, that's never clever,

00:33:35.300 --> 00:33:37.000
but you might have to
work very hard [laughter].

00:33:44.060 --> 00:33:45.950
&gt;&gt; I studied with Bill [inaudible]

00:33:45.950 --> 00:33:47.250
&gt;&gt; -- microphone.

00:33:47.250 --> 00:33:49.960
&gt;&gt; I'm sorry, I studied with
Bill Bales, who was early Graham

00:33:49.960 --> 00:33:53.180
and it was very swoopy,
much more lyrical.

00:33:53.180 --> 00:33:56.570
I was at the studio
in the 50s and 60s

00:33:56.570 --> 00:33:59.530
which had become much more
percussive and angular.

00:33:59.530 --> 00:34:05.270 position:56%
Has the technique itself evolved as
it seemed to do while she was alive?

00:34:05.270 --> 00:34:09.930
&gt;&gt; Janet Eilber: Yes and she
lived for such a long time

00:34:09.930 --> 00:34:15.060
that she set us a good
example because the physicality

00:34:15.060 --> 00:34:17.790
of each generation keeps changing.

00:34:17.790 --> 00:34:22.300
It's like the Olympics every
few years people break a record.

00:34:22.300 --> 00:34:25.060
The legs go higher, the jumps
go higher, the turns are faster,

00:34:25.060 --> 00:34:28.120
the falls you know, and
Martha actually loved that

00:34:28.120 --> 00:34:32.080
and would keep incorporating
it into her classroom exercises

00:34:32.080 --> 00:34:35.270
and her choreography as
she was creating new work

00:34:35.270 --> 00:34:38.920
but also into the classic works.

00:34:38.920 --> 00:34:44.770
She didn't expect us to dance
like the casts from 1947 or 1957

00:34:44.770 --> 00:34:47.090
or 1967 had danced the works.

00:34:47.090 --> 00:34:53.840
She wanted to use our facility
and the effort was she wanted

00:34:53.840 --> 00:34:57.370
to maintain the dramatic intent.

00:34:57.370 --> 00:35:00.980
She felt that that could happen,
that you could let the legs go

00:35:00.980 --> 00:35:05.170
that you could use the facility
of the contemporary dancers and

00:35:05.170 --> 00:35:09.850
yet remain true to the message of
the work so that's a lesson I take

00:35:09.850 --> 00:35:16.520
from Martha and of course today's
dancers are absolutely astounding.

00:35:16.520 --> 00:35:19.640
The job is to use that
in the service

00:35:19.640 --> 00:35:22.770
of the dramatic intent of the work.

00:35:25.940 --> 00:35:28.830
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: Anyone else?

00:35:28.830 --> 00:35:33.190
I think - oh yeah one there, okay.

00:35:33.190 --> 00:35:35.520
&gt;&gt; Hi, I was curious, the dance

00:35:35.520 --> 00:35:39.900
that you choreographed did
you have an idea of the dance

00:35:39.900 --> 00:35:44.370 position:56%
and then apply the music to the
dance or did you listen to the music

00:35:44.370 --> 00:35:48.150
and then create the
dance from the music?

00:35:48.150 --> 00:35:52.340
&gt;&gt; Pontus Lidberg: I listen
to the music first and I work

00:35:52.340 --> 00:35:53.950
in many different ways actually.

00:35:53.950 --> 00:35:57.920
I work in both of those ways
in combinations of the two

00:35:57.920 --> 00:36:00.700
and I didn't decide
which way I would work

00:36:00.700 --> 00:36:03.070
because first I did research.

00:36:03.070 --> 00:36:08.100
I didn't even choose the music
straight away I had some pieces.

00:36:08.100 --> 00:36:11.280 position:56%
In fact I chose another piece first
that I really wanted to choreograph.

00:36:11.280 --> 00:36:14.710
I think it's a beautiful piece
of music, great for dance,

00:36:14.710 --> 00:36:16.080
called Serious Song for Strings

00:36:16.080 --> 00:36:19.540
but then I had a problem
combining it with something else.

00:36:19.540 --> 00:36:24.150
It was such a standalone piece
and as such it was too short

00:36:24.150 --> 00:36:32.770
so I changed my mind but I think
one of the challenges of working

00:36:32.770 --> 00:36:35.990
with Irving Fein's music
is that it is particular.

00:36:35.990 --> 00:36:39.480
There is a lot of music that is
popular among choreographers today

00:36:39.480 --> 00:36:46.940
that is more like a
landscape or an ambience

00:36:46.940 --> 00:36:49.670
that goes on for a long time.

00:36:49.670 --> 00:36:54.210
It's less specific but this music
is very specific and so I found

00:36:54.210 --> 00:36:58.870
that it would be difficult for me
to superimpose something on that.

00:36:58.870 --> 00:37:02.460
It just didn't work
so then I decided well

00:37:02.460 --> 00:37:05.650
in that case I will really work
with the music and listen to it

00:37:05.650 --> 00:37:12.130
and choreograph what I hear
and work with it that way so in

00:37:12.130 --> 00:37:13.840 position:56%
that way it's not a conceptual piece

00:37:13.840 --> 00:37:15.660
because sometimes I
do conceptual pieces

00:37:15.660 --> 00:37:19.350 position:56%
and then you choose all the
elements that strengthen the concept

00:37:19.350 --> 00:37:21.350
but this is not one of them.

00:37:21.350 --> 00:37:25.760
This is a musical piece and it's
also the encounter with the dancers

00:37:25.760 --> 00:37:28.730
and the encounter with the
music is really the piece.

00:37:28.730 --> 00:37:32.190
&gt;&gt; Do you let the dancers
contribute to the choreography?

00:37:32.190 --> 00:37:33.990
&gt;&gt; Pontus Lidberg: Yes.

00:37:33.990 --> 00:37:37.040
[ Inaudible ]

00:37:37.040 --> 00:37:38.430
Yes I can explain that [laughter].

00:37:38.430 --> 00:37:46.370
As a young choreographer I was very
interested in creating steps not

00:37:46.370 --> 00:37:49.390
to the point of codifying a
technique or anything like that

00:37:49.390 --> 00:37:54.720
but I was certainly interested
in this is my step which is

00:37:54.720 --> 00:38:00.280
of course not really true
because the patterns that you move

00:38:00.280 --> 00:38:03.860
in are conditioned so
they are not mine at all

00:38:03.860 --> 00:38:07.750
but anyway I was interested
in making the choices.

00:38:07.750 --> 00:38:11.310
This is the step, this is the
phrase, this is the sequence,

00:38:11.310 --> 00:38:14.670
these are the angles, this is
the you know all of it and I did

00:38:14.670 --> 00:38:16.700
that for quite a long
time to the point

00:38:16.700 --> 00:38:19.110
where that wasn't inspiring anymore

00:38:19.110 --> 00:38:24.440 position:56%
but rather I started being more
interested in seeing what can I draw

00:38:24.440 --> 00:38:29.680
out of someone else and so then
I kind of just throw a ball

00:38:29.680 --> 00:38:33.930
and then see what they do with it
and from then I start like okay

00:38:33.930 --> 00:38:37.990 position:56%
and I saw something in what they did
and I said actually if you just do

00:38:37.990 --> 00:38:41.320
with slightly different,
go this way instead,

00:38:41.320 --> 00:38:42.620
and that way it's conversational

00:38:42.620 --> 00:38:47.380
so I can shape the
choreography with the dancers.

00:38:47.380 --> 00:38:51.230
The strange thing is that
the choreography always,

00:38:51.230 --> 00:38:54.590
well to this point at least,
turns out instantly recognizable

00:38:54.590 --> 00:38:58.340 position:56%
as my choreography even though I
don't give steps anymore [laughter].

00:39:02.030 --> 00:39:05.370
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: Maybe one
more question, over there.

00:39:05.370 --> 00:39:06.670
&gt;&gt; This is wonderful.

00:39:06.670 --> 00:39:11.000
I'm learning about Martha Graham's
approach and style to dance.

00:39:11.000 --> 00:39:13.720
What else will be demonstrated

00:39:13.720 --> 00:39:16.400
about her particular style
in the pieces tonight?

00:39:16.400 --> 00:39:20.070
You mentioned a few other things.

00:39:20.070 --> 00:39:21.760
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: What else
will be demonstrated?

00:39:21.760 --> 00:39:26.030
&gt;&gt; That's peculiar
to Martha's approach.

00:39:26.030 --> 00:39:29.020
&gt;&gt; Janet Eilber: To Martha's
style and her vocabulary?

00:39:29.020 --> 00:39:34.110
Well tonight's program actually
the three Graham works give you a

00:39:34.110 --> 00:39:38.830
wonderful overview of
several different periods.

00:39:38.830 --> 00:39:42.200
You know she lived so long
it's almost like Picasso

00:39:42.200 --> 00:39:48.590
and Appalachian Spring of course
is from her Americana period

00:39:48.590 --> 00:39:52.540
and Dark Meadow and these dances
are fairly close together.

00:39:52.540 --> 00:39:57.210
Appalachian Springs '44,
Dark Meadows '47 and Cave

00:39:57.210 --> 00:40:06.050
of the Heart is '46 but Dark Meadow
is very abstract modernist work.

00:40:06.050 --> 00:40:13.360
The chorus work is very
geometric and the patterns

00:40:13.360 --> 00:40:18.180
that the dancers make on the stage
really harken back to experiments

00:40:18.180 --> 00:40:22.190
that she did in the early 1930s
before she started using the Gucci

00:40:22.190 --> 00:40:26.760
sets, experimenting with the
geometry of the stage and the lines

00:40:26.760 --> 00:40:31.990
of force and drawing inspiration
from Guggenheim Fellowship she had

00:40:31.990 --> 00:40:38.140
where she traveled and lived in the
Southwest and visited the rituals

00:40:38.140 --> 00:40:40.190
of the Pueblo communities there.

00:40:40.190 --> 00:40:44.990
There's a lot of the Southwest
and the Native American ritual

00:40:44.990 --> 00:40:49.670
in several of Graham's works
and particularly in Dark Meadow

00:40:49.670 --> 00:40:52.550
and then Cave of the
Heart inspired one

00:40:52.550 --> 00:40:56.560
of her wonderful Greek
works by Medea.

00:40:56.560 --> 00:41:01.530 position:56%
Again of course she's a modernist so
the thing about Cave of the Heart is

00:41:01.530 --> 00:41:06.170
that she distilled the story
into only four characters

00:41:06.170 --> 00:41:11.930
to represent this emotional battle
of Medea and Jason the princess

00:41:11.930 --> 00:41:18.510
and the chorus so you're
really getting a nice view

00:41:18.510 --> 00:41:21.740
of different approaches,
different inspirations for Martha

00:41:21.740 --> 00:41:26.190
but I do encourage you
to watch for those torsos

00:41:26.190 --> 00:41:32.610 position:56%
because really everything comes -- ,
even when a Graham dancer lifts his

00:41:32.610 --> 00:41:38.480 position:56%
or her arm it's because the shoulder
blade is dropping down the back

00:41:38.480 --> 00:41:42.230
and you are leveraging the power
from the floor to lift that arm.

00:41:42.230 --> 00:41:44.030
It's never just a simple arm.

00:41:44.030 --> 00:41:47.050
I have to demonstrate one thing.

00:41:47.050 --> 00:41:49.790
When a baseball pitcher pitches,

00:41:49.790 --> 00:41:52.510
when I watch a baseball
pitcher pitch I see him first go

00:41:52.510 --> 00:41:54.690
into big Martha Graham contraction
[laughter], so if home plate is

00:41:54.690 --> 00:42:01.530
down there -- , he comes way
back here, his torso is coiled,

00:42:01.530 --> 00:42:04.780
it's leveraging off the
mound and he throws the ball

00:42:04.780 --> 00:42:06.350
from the center of
the planet, right?

00:42:06.350 --> 00:42:07.970
He presses away.

00:42:07.970 --> 00:42:12.280
All of the energy goes all the way
through the release of the torso,

00:42:12.280 --> 00:42:16.180
the contraction and bam
the ball goes, right?

00:42:16.180 --> 00:42:19.480
So a Graham dancer does
not dance like this.

00:42:19.480 --> 00:42:23.040
Every movement is coming
from the center of the body

00:42:23.040 --> 00:42:26.040
from the floor so look for it.

00:42:26.040 --> 00:42:28.500
They're not going to throw a ball
at you but they're throwing energy

00:42:28.500 --> 00:42:31.350
in the same way [laughter].

00:42:31.350 --> 00:42:33.440
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: Wonderful,
that's a great way to end.

00:42:33.440 --> 00:42:36.810
I think we're about to the point
of going into the concert hall.

00:42:36.810 --> 00:42:38.870
Please take a look at
our exhibits by the way.

00:42:38.870 --> 00:42:42.510
We have a lot of interesting
material and thank you so much.

00:42:42.510 --> 00:42:55.530
[ Applause ]

